r, Ireland":"Munster, Irska","Ireland":"Irska","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irska"},"cs":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irsko"},"da":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irland"},"nl":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacCarthy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish:  see  McCarthy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCarthy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Liam, Cormac, Niall, Aileen, Brigid, Conor, Declan, Dermod, Dermot, Finbar.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cárthaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Cárthach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘loving’. This was the name of a ruling family in Munster. In Ireland major branches were distinguished by the following epithets: <i>mór</i> ‘great’ in Kerry, <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled’ in Carbery, west Cork."]}]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Amy MacCarthy was born in 1352, in Ireland, her father, Donal McCarthy V King of Desmond, was 49 and her mother, Jeanne Fitz Gerald, was 38. She married John de La Roche in 1374, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1375, in her hometown, at the age of 23."},"et":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1352–1375":"1352–1375","1340–1413":"1340–1413","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1375–1439":"1375–1439","1303–1390":"1303–1390","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1413":"1413","1365":"1365","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1439":"1439","Muskerry, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Munster, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Ferm